{"abstained": false, "answer": "The document defines the law of good Gestalt as follows: \"Elements of objects tend to be perceptually grouped together if they form a pattern that is regular, simple, and orderly.\" This law suggests that individuals perceive the world by eliminating complexity and unfamiliarity to observe a reality in its most simplistic form. It also implies that the mind creates meaning through this process, prioritizing global regularity over spatial relations, and focuses on the idea of conciseness, which is central to gestalt theory.", "cache_key": "c6fec962fe1e1edb90577132a2091ac7182ac16426dedb2da834d69fdc201e22", "condition": "oracle", "correct": true, "doc_id": "0e94b4197b10096b1f4c699701570fbf.pdf", "doc_type": "Tutorial/Workshop", "evidence_sources": ["Pure-text (Plain-text)"], "hop": "single", "input_text_tokens": 185, "input_visual_tokens": 0, "is_unanswerable": false, "judge_spec": "generate-throwaway", "latency_s": 4.537417467683554, "metadata": {"note": "", "source_dataset": "mmlongbench"}, "model_spec": "internvl3-8b-local", "output_tokens": 82, "page_indices": [10], "provenance": "oracle", "question_id": "mmlongbench:000016", "representation": "T", "score": 1.0}
{"abstained": false, "answer": "The document defines the law of good gestalt as follows: \"Elements of objects tend to be perceptually grouped together if they form a pattern that is regular, simple, and orderly. This law implies that as individuals perceive the world, they eliminate complexity and unfamiliarity so they can observe a reality in its most simplistic form. Eliminating extraneous stimuli helps the mind create meaning.\" The law focuses on the idea of conciseness, which is what all of gestalt theory is based on.", "cache_key": "3ee9a5b245a58b5cea9b359ddabd7128070e7f656874e786acb8300a695a09ce", "condition": "oracle", "correct": true, "doc_id": "0e94b4197b10096b1f4c699701570fbf.pdf", "doc_type": "Tutorial/Workshop", "evidence_sources": ["Pure-text (Plain-text)"], "hop": "single", "input_text_tokens": 775, "input_visual_tokens": 0, "is_unanswerable": false, "judge_spec": "generate-throwaway", "latency_s": 5.384144315496087, "metadata": {"note": "", "source_dataset": "mmlongbench"}, "model_spec": "internvl3-8b-local", "output_tokens": 81, "page_indices": [10], "provenance": "oracle", "question_id": "mmlongbench:000016", "representation": "TL", "score": 1.0}
{"abstained": false, "answer": "The law of good Gestalt is defined as the tendency of elements of objects to be perceptually grouped together if they form a pattern that is regular, simple, and orderly. This law suggests that individuals perceive the world by eliminating complexity and unfamiliarity to observe reality in its most simplistic form. By eliminating extraneous stimuli, the mind creates meaning, which is often mentally prioritized over spatial relations. The law emphasizes the idea of conciseness, which is fundamental to gestalt theory.", "cache_key": "0917c4a9d8fd01636a154683298d5a2eb284a70c7c328740b113f5946d4c3600", "condition": "oracle", "correct": false, "doc_id": "0e94b4197b10096b1f4c699701570fbf.pdf", "doc_type": "Tutorial/Workshop", "evidence_sources": ["Pure-text (Plain-text)"], "hop": "single", "input_text_tokens": 776, "input_visual_tokens": 1024, "is_unanswerable": false, "judge_spec": "generate-throwaway", "latency_s": 5.622336326166987, "metadata": {"note": "", "source_dataset": "mmlongbench"}, "model_spec": "internvl3-8b-local", "output_tokens": 80, "page_indices": [10], "provenance": "oracle", "question_id": "mmlongbench:000016", "representation": "TLV", "score": 0.0}
{"abstained": false, "answer": "The law of good Gestalt is defined in the document as follows: \"Elements of objects tend to be perceptually grouped together if they form a pattern that is regular, simple, and orderly. This law implies that as individuals perceive the world, they eliminate complexity and unfamiliarity so they can observe a reality in its most simplistic form. Stimuli helped the mind create meaning. This meaning created by perception implies a global regularity, which is often mentally prioritized over spatial relations. The law of good gestalt focuses on the idea of conciseness, which is what all of gestalt theory is based on.\"", "cache_key": "c44cf5426056df528979df02d2b73ff575f04f79a231ead6217d9418ceeacddd", "condition": "oracle", "correct": true, "doc_id": "0e94b4197b10096b1f4c699701570fbf.pdf", "doc_type": "Tutorial/Workshop", "evidence_sources": ["Pure-text (Plain-text)"], "hop": "single", "input_text_tokens": 56, "input_visual_tokens": 1024, "is_unanswerable": false, "judge_spec": "generate-throwaway", "latency_s": 5.842794807627797, "metadata": {"note": "", "source_dataset": "mmlongbench"}, "model_spec": "internvl3-8b-local", "output_tokens": 101, "page_indices": [10], "provenance": "oracle", "question_id": "mmlongbench:000016", "representation": "V", "score": 1.0}
